  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/morrison-cou1-decision-001",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-lead",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The CFD hemolysis model for the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump under CPB conditions is accepted for the declared COU at MRL 2. The assessment is grounded in the following structured evidence: (1) All seven assessed credibility factors meet or exceed their required levels for MRL 2: Software QA (achieved 2 ≥ required 1), Code Verification (achieved 2 ≥ required 1), Discretization Error (achieved 3 ≥ required 2, GCI = 1.8%), Test Conditions (achieved 2 = required 2), Output Comparison (achieved 3 ≥ required 2, max error 4.7%), QoI Relevance (achieved 2 = required 2), and Validation Relevance (achieved 2 = required 2). (2) Six factors are appropriately scoped out under ASME V&V 40-2018 Table 3 provisions for MRL 2 with commercial solver and direct geometric equivalence. (3) The declared operating envelope (flow 2–6 L/min, speed 2000–4000 RPM, hematocrit 35–45%) is explicitly bounded, and validation activities cover all five operating points including both lower-bound and upper-bound corners of the flow-speed space, confirming that model predictions satisfy RH < 1 across the full envelope. (4) Uncertainty quantification at each operating point demonstrates that 95% confidence intervals remain below the RH = 1.0 acceptance threshold, including at the highest-hemolysis operating point (OP2: CI upper bound 0.97). (5) The applicability constraint explicitly limits model use to centrifugal pump geometries similar to the FDA generic pump with Newtonian fluid rheology, preventing inappropriate extrapolation. The provenance chain from experimental measurements through validation results to this credibility assessment is complete and traceable. The decision to accept is supported by the totality of the structured evidence and is consistent with the MRL 2 requirements for a Class II CPB device.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
